Dangote Cement Plc has announced the successful issuance of its N100 billion Series 1 Fixed Rate Senior Unsecured Bonds due April 2025 under the company’s N300 billion Bond Programme. According to the company’s management, the transaction was 1.5 times oversubscribed and represents the company’s first bond issuance in the debt capital markets. Book building with respect to the issuance commenced on 3rd April, 2020 following approval from the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) and closed on 15 April 2020 at a coupon rate of 12.50 percent. The issuer stated that despite current market headwinds associated with the COVID-19 pandemic, the transaction was well received, attracting demand from a wide range of investors including domestic pension funds, asset managers, insurance companies, banks and international fund managers. The total order book amounted to N155 billion. The transaction represents the largest corporate bond issuance in Nigeria’s debt capital markets, reflecting the issuer’s strong credit quality as well as the resilience of the Nigerian debt capital market despite current global challenges. Commenting on the bond issuance, the company’s CEO, Michel Puchercos, said: “This landmark transaction is the largest ever bond issuance by a corporate issuer in Nigeria. It allows us to further broaden our sources of funding by accessing long-term debt at competitive costs from the capital market and builds further on the success of our domestic commercial paper programme.” The bonds will be listed on the Nigerian Stock Exchange and the FMDQ Securities Exchange Limited, and for the first time in the history of the Nigerian debt capital markets, investors will have the option of lodging securities with either the Central Securities Clearing System or the FMDQ Depository. Dangote Cement to raise N100bn through bond issuance NSP Ltd issues N8.5bn 1st corporate green infrastructure bond FG to issue N20bn 30-year bond on April 24